    <div class="onecolumn">
        <a name="reattach"></a>
        <h1>Re-Attaching jGeez events</h1>
          <p>During the full life span of a page, there are times when you might need to restructure your DOM (document object model) 
          . It might be to animate you divs or show html driven popup dialog boxes but those actions will disrupt the HTML structure of your page, there by causing the events attached on those elements to vanish
          into thin air.
          in this circumstances apply jgeez again on the element would create multiple toggle buttons and 
          just breaks the flow of jGeez. use the following code to reattach events to your jGeez plugin
          </p> 
          <div class="sample_code" style="width:870px;margin:5px;">
            &lt;script type=&quot;text/javascript&quot;&gt;
            <br />
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <span class="green">$(document).ready(function () {
                <br />
                &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <span style="color: Gray;">//add this snippit after the code that resturcture your DOM in click events or functions</span>
                <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; $(&quot;#geeztextbox
                &quot;).jGeez('reattachevents');
                <br />
                &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; }); </span>
            <br />
            &lt;/script&gt;</div>
            <h3 class="remarks">remarks</h3>
            <ul class="remarks">
                <li>this function only works after jgeez plugin is applied on an element</li>
                <li>there is no need to check if the event is already attached, this function does that work before attaching more events</li>
                <li>there is no need to call this method for ajax calls since jGeez by default attempts to reattach
                events after every ajax call</li>
            </ul>
    </div>


    <div class="onecolumn">
        <h1><a name="attributeimplimentation" /> Implementation by Attribute</h1>
        <p>
            One of the main features introduced from the release of jGeez 1.1.0.0 is using Attributes of html elements 
            to control the behaviour of jGeez on our developments. Just to start of I want to limit the definition of Attribute as below
            to avoid confusion with the diverse meaning for the word "attribute"
        </p> 

        <p>
            <b>Attribute of an element </b> : is a name value pair separtated by "=" and written within the start tag of an element.common example of a typical
            attribute use is like :<br /> 
            
            
        </p>
            <div class="sample_code" style="width:870px;margin:5px;">
                    <span class="green">&ltimg src=&quotphoto.png&quot /&gt </span> 
            </div>
        <p>
            in which <b>src</b> is the attribute and <b>photo.png</b>  is the value
        </p>

        <p>
            So in jGeez you can use custom attributes on elements to define geez behaviours on input elements, labels and even the overall behaviour of how deep the 
            library is going to integrate it self into your web application. these custom attributes are detailed in the coming sections with 
            example for each of the elements you can apply attributes to.
        </p>

        <p>
            with this simplicity comes some limitations to using this library, although not significant enough it
            is worth mentioning this remarks when walking down the "implementation by attribute" feature:
        </p>
         <ul class="remarks">
                <li>you can not change options using attributes once the library is fully loaded on the client browser</li>
                <li>since the library and style info is online, this library would only work when the user is online.
                    you will have to disable the attribute implementation and follow the quick implementation to use the library off line or on an 
                    intranet environment
                </li>
         </ul>
    </div>

